{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488250"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"393"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/393"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.51,0.21,0.2,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96638"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/393"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"393"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79272"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"782"},{"type":"tags","id":"1186"},{"type":"tags","id":"1214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2755"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10781"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10870"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96638"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with pain in his right arm. He felt a \u0022pop\u0022 in his right arm whilst moving heavy furniture yesterday. He states it was immediately painful and he was unable to continue lifting heavy objects. Today, he noticed a swelling on the anterior right arm at the site of the pain. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a visible bulge in the anterior aspect of his right arm (Image) with associated tenderness on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immobilisation in a sling for four weeks","Conservative management with rest, ice and analgesia","Arthroscopic repair","Open surgical repair","Rehabilitation with heavy weight exercises"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic history and examination findings of a proximal biceps tendon rupture. The sudden \u0022pop\u0022 during exertion, immediate pain, and subsequent anterior arm swelling (often described as a \u0022Popeye deformity\u0022) are characteristic features. The proximal biceps tendon contributes to stability at the glenohumeral joint but is not critical for normal arm function in most patients.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConservative management with rest, ice and analgesia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach for proximal biceps tendon ruptures, particularly in older patients. Most patients regain nearly full function with conservative treatment, and the cosmetic deformity is often acceptable, especially in this 60-year-old patient. Conservative management typically includes a short period of rest, ice application, analgesics, and gradual return to activities, followed by appropriate rehabilitation exercises.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmobilisation in a sling for four weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is overly restrictive for a proximal biceps tendon rupture. While a brief period of sling use (a few days) may provide comfort, prolonged immobilisation can lead to shoulder stiffness and is not necessary for healing of this injury. Early, controlled movement is generally encouraged.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArthroscopic repair\u003C/strong\u003E is rarely indicated for isolated proximal biceps tendon ruptures in older patients. Surgical intervention for proximal biceps tendon ruptures is generally reserved for younger, high-demand patients or athletes where functional demands are higher. The functional deficit from a proximal biceps rupture is minimal in most patients, making surgery unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpen surgical repair\u003C/strong\u003E of proximal biceps tendon ruptures is similarly not routinely recommended for the same reasons as arthroscopic repair. It\u0027s worth noting that distal biceps tendon ruptures (at the elbow) are managed differently and often do require surgical repair to restore forearm supination strength.\u003C/p\u003E\n\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERehabilitation with heavy weight exercises\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in the acute phase of a biceps tendon rupture. Heavy resistance training could exacerbate the injury and cause further damage. Appropriate rehabilitation should begin with gentle range of motion exercises, progressing gradually to light resistance as symptoms improve, under the guidance of a physiotherapist.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Proximal biceps tendon rupture typically presents with a painful \u0022pop\u0022 followed by anterior arm swelling.","Conservative management is appropriate for proximal biceps tendon ruptures, especially in older patients.","Surgical intervention is more commonly indicated for distal biceps tendon ruptures."],"references":["Hsu D, Anand P, Chang KV. Biceps Tendon Rupture. In: StatPearls [Internet]. [Updated 2020 Nov 2]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513235/","Lalehzarian SP, Agarwalla A, Liu JN. Management of proximal biceps tendon pathology. World J Orthop. 2022 Jan 18;13(1):36-57. doi: 10.5312/wjo.v13.i1.36. PMID: 35096535; PMCID: PMC8771414. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8771414/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79272"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"393"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"10434"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"10434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/10434"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4f4dfa20-9e52-4e81-a721-de8982c58ecb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4f4dfa20-9e52-4e81-a721-de8982c58ecb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79272","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79272"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T14:51:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T14:51:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"393"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","syn